description.text:
the slightest of remix of the bed mount https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1915486/#files

ok didnt plan on doing this update but saw a way to gain more clearance just in case.

FRAME MOUNT
the frame mount still may change as i got a slight warp in the printing and i now have a measurement to modify tabs just like i did on the bed mount went from 1mm clearance of hot end passing over chain to between 6mm and 8mm by extending the mount 3 chain lengths out and removing those links.

i left the entire bottom open so those of you that clipped the chains dont need to rewire tho im getting pretty good at it myself.

again you need to fix manifold issue with quick fix when i get a 100% im not gonna do anything else to it i will recreate the whole thing from scratch since my cad will not create a solid of the original file for some reason.

BED MOUNT
added a slight angle to top of area that connects to the cable chain thus causing the chain to not be able to arch enough to come into contact with hot end.

i actually found that i could prevent this by adding a spare m4 washer in the link at the mount but did not want to leave it like that because it pushed outwards causing a rub of frame. so took the dimensions and added it to the upper portion only so the travel was prevented evenly.

my cad program did not like the original files and would not allow me to make the object manifold.it allowed me to attach the additions but not make it one piece just click fix in repetier or which ever program you use to auto fix.

for those who still wanting more clearance and be sure you cannot hit hot end consider using the mirror feature and mounting it on the right side of the machine instead.

Yes

knew that the cable chain allowed itself to go beyond 180* so in order to prevent this with minimal amount of parts replaced i added tabs to the existing hotbed mount after finding a m4 washer took up enough slack to not allow the hot end to make contact

i was not happy with it still getting close to hot end even if i cleared it enough to not be a issue and noticed that the first 3 lower links werent needed and they actually moved upward when fully in even tho the slack wasnt needed i couldve just glued the links stationary and done the same thing but why not fix the problem from being someone elses as well

title: Segmented Interlocking Well spacer for UARM-Pro Experimental Pathology Stainer / Deparaffinization Platform

description.text:
This is a segmented interlocking well spacer for a URAM swift Pro Immunohistochemistry and deparaffinization central axis automated robotic work station.

The wells are spaced evenly around the central base of a four axis robotic arm.
Using the same robotic arm with the Groove attachments it should be possible to:

1) Perform complex automated immunohistochemistry protocols
2) Perform Deparaphjinnization protocols
3) using the magnetic head attachment, pick up and deposit staining racks
4) Laser engrave slides for processing
5) Laser ablate non-tumor tissue on slides to "enhance for tumor" in genomic studies
6) Pneumatic head attachment, pick up individual microscope slides
7) Universal gripper, pick up and deposit slides for In Situ Hybridization on Peltier block
8) perform complex preprogrammed sequences by Gestrue control
9) Enable onboard image feature recognition to enable interactive protocols
10) link / Mesh several workstations together to perform work concurrently or interactively.

Staining wells for reagents can be alternated with draining or blotting containers or there may be a second ring for special procedures (delivering slides to a heating platform for in Situ hybridization / PCR.

This design is suitable for Auto Immuno Stainers, Histochemistry stainers, deparaphinization procedures etc...

All parts may be milled as a 2D DXF or 3D printed.

Designed in TrueSpace 7.6 and subsequently milled using a Flashcut refurbished MAXNC CNC milling machine from 1/8' thick wood plates. The individual segments have angled edges (22.5 degrees) and are interlocking. The wells may be of any appropriate material and the segments are designed to have a 5 cm base.

Programming movements for staining and Deparaffinization protocols will be perfomed using both MBlock graphical programming and OffLine Teach mode.

Dimensions: 12.499x4.996x1.0 cm

Deparaffinization procedure: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q_ls0QAtzy0

When you go to install this, you may have to sand the posts down just a little where the dial meets the gear teeth. I broke both of mine, so I had to replace both parts from shattered parts. I dont know what the actual original posts looked like, so I kinda guessed.

I quickly sanded down any blobs on the posts on the inside with a micro file.

I used 100 grit paper to sand the middle post on the inside so that it was nice and flat. Then used 220 on it quickly to make it smooth. Same to the very bottom of the dial (flat outer ring).

I used 100 grit paper to sand the outside of the dial, and did it until it was basically smooth, and free of major defections. I finished it with a heavy amount of 220 until it was super smooth. I didn't focus too much under where the screw head goes.

I did a nice even coat of filler primer, let it dry, a quick sanding at 220, a second coat, let it dry, sprayed it with a matte black enamel, let it dry, second coat, let it dry, then sprayed it with a clear enamel. Let it dry completely for a few days, probably don't need to.

description.text:
Why spend $5.95 (US) on a replacement part when you can spend $$$ on a 3D printer, filament, replacement parts, etc.? Because you can!

This is my first creation, start to finish. It is a replacement tent support tip for my Coleman popup tent trailer. The original tip had sheared off. I had to drill it out in chunks, because of the tight fit.

I made this in OpenSCAD, printed a hollow .1mm thick test on quick print settings (Cura 15.04, Hictop 3DP-17), and adjusted the model in OpenSCAD once (test print was the same diameter as the outside of the pole - forgot to subtract wall thickness). This is the final version.

I printed it in high quality mode with 45% infill for strength, using PLA (I haven't gotten any ABS yet). Took a bit of sanding to get it to fit in the support pipe, but the tip turned out perfect. And it only took 1.5 hours to do the final print, which I installed just before the rains hit (otherwise the roof would collect water and leak).

Update:
Well, the original survived my week of camping, but when I came home and setup the trailer to clean it out, the tip sheared off. So much for 45% infill.

I wanted to reprint with 100% infill, but even on quick print, it would take a lot of material. So, back to OpenSCAD for a quick edit.

This new version has a hollow base with a 2mm wall thickness. The rest is unchanged. 100% infill now prints in ~2 hours.

comments.text: Good question of course. Still testing this. I made this version to see what the 40mm blower can do and as a cheaper alternative. Both shrouds focus the airstream very nicely. Either one will solve the problem you describe. But it all depends on how fast you print and what kind of object (size, overhangs etc). Also consider how hot the bed runs as this will increase the temp of the air available for cooling. I use the 50mm version at 100% for PLA printing at 60-90mm/s. Also you have the power available for large bridges if need be. The 40mm fan works nicely at 100% for PETG at 30mm/s but I still have upwards bend overhangs with PLA and small objects can still have problems. ABS will be fine as well with the 40mm. For sure a big improvement over the stock fan. However, I like the 50mm blower. It is expensive (german engineering I guess) but it is rated for 30000 hours and runs really smoothly. It is in a different league. Not sure how the cheaper blowers will last in the high temperature environment (basically close to the bed temp). Before deciding to fix the cooling situation on the printer I blew through 6 cheap regular fans in 6 month on a double fan shroud. They started to create a lot of vibrations and noise. I guess the output of the stock fans is rather low and even directed away from the nozzle to prevent heating failures. That problem went away with the silicone boots. No reason not to have enough cooling anymore.

  • solder all LEDs in parallel (< 4x20mm big)

  • wire batteries from both Lilypad battery holders in parallel
  • connect one of the holders to the RGB LED assembly
Soldered RGB LED assembly and wiring up battery holders. Step 2: Assemble battery holders and LEDs with housing
  • snap in both battery holders into the bottom case part
  • affix the LEDs to the front case part using black gaffer tape
Tape RGB LED assembly in place using black gaffer tape Step 3: Click the skate bearing into place

Click the bearing into place, don't use no glue at this step. You might want to clean your bearing with Isopropyl alcohol for higher speeds due to grease-removal.

title: Penny Spinner Large, Small and Tiny  626-zz

description.text:
Seems many create or print a spinner/fidget at some time with their 3D printer. Well, my turn and I only have a box of 626ZZ bearings. No luck finding a print file with all 19mm x 6mm holes. So I created a simple curve design with 6mm inserts to epoxy pennies to. As it turns out the big one, with all shiny new 2017 coins, is a tad bit too big for me to spin in hand by the outside bearing. For the small one I dug through my coin jar to find real copper pennies.

Anyway, interesting toy ... fun to make.

It's easier faster and less chance of glue on bearing if button to penny epoxy sets before inserting into the bearing. On the other hand it's easier to center the 19mm penny with the 19mm bearing if the button is inserted first. The latter risks epoxy squishing out and interfering with rotation so a little dab will do ya. And you'll likely need to mix a batch of epoxy for each side.

I added a Tiny spinner file and smaller lower profile glue buttons (my favorites). Also, added a button to penny centering jig, Another file update 5/20 is the single centering jig much easier than the 8 position jig.

The jigs are reusable and easiest to clean out glue blobs if the penny is removed before completely setting up e.g. about 15-20min with a 5min epoxy. Once clamped it is best to pop the insert so the clamp foot is flush with the bottom making a gap between the penny and the jig. Let it dry upside-down to prevent bonding the jig to penny and insert.

title: John Deere 1 series tractor seat belt stop
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: If you own a John Deere 1 series TLB or FILB tractor and your like me, you find the seat belt setup frustrating and annoying. If you leave them up and tighten them down, you can't turn the seat around. But if you leave them loose, they flop around and damage the inside of your fenders, and your levers. So the trick is to leave them just loose enough so they can be moved around, but yet stay in place without falling. Problem is, over time they come loose and fall down anyway if you don't lock them down super tight. Which takes you back to the first problem again! So this is my attempt at a fix for this. These stops simply slide over the seat belt bracket, and you bolt the seat belt through them. The 180° flat edge stops the seat belt from rotating any further than necessary. This will require slightly longer bolts. Or you can just do what I did for now and turn your nylon lock nut around and thread it on with a washer. Now you can have a free moving seat belt without it damaging your tractor, or getting in the way of turning the seat around. Plus you can still use your seat belt if you wish! I had one of these stops slide on perfect on one side, and the other required a bit of force. Probably variances in the metal bracket itself, or the paint on the bracket could be thicker in different spots. But they both did fit my 1025r TLB perfectly fine. These are a trial and error kind of design, so only time will tell if this is a good fix or not. Enjoy!

description.text:
This is a yet another tool holder for the Lulzbot Mini 3D printer. Unlike many other designs, this does not clip on & hang over the top frame. Rather, I designed it to be mounted flush directly to the printer's frame side wall, like a wall-mount cabinet.

I designed this to hold all the tools that come with the the Mini printer, plus the following additional tools:

  • Husky digital caliper
  • Titan razor blade scraper
  • Jonard cutter
  • Hyde 1.5in wide putty knife
  • General hobby knife plus extra blades
  • iFixIt jimmy/spudger
  • glue stick (up to 25mm diameter)

Notes:

I used eSUN black 3mm PLA filament. I printed it upside down to avoid having a massive clean-up job from supports. The holes with bottoms have a heavy fillet internally, so the printer can build them up without having to print supports.

With these settings, it takes about 5hr to print.

Supplies

There are a total of 6 screw holes in the design, but in practice you'll only need 4 of them. You might even get away with just two.

  • 4x (or 6x) M3 10mm black anodized screws (flat 2mm hex head). My local Orchard Supply hardware store carries them as part #88686
  • 2mm hex screwdriver; the thinner shaft, the better (no more than 8mm thick for the first 30mm or so).
Installation

This assumes you're only using 4 screws. I found that to be plenty.

  1. Remove the two screws above the power supply, in the corner at the back of the printer.
  2. Remove the two screws above the power supply, around halfway from the back of the printer. That is, the middle pair of the screws that hold the top bracket for the vertical threaded rods that move the print head up and down.
  3. Insert the replacement screws into their respective holes in the tool holder. I recommend starting with the top-left corner because it is the most cumbersome to reach.

The actual design is pretty simple. The challenges were:

  • Deciding how to lay out the tools, taking into account not just the hole needed but also how much space the tool handle might (or might not) need above it.
  • Measuring the screw hole locations accurately. I was astonished to get them right on the first shot.
  • Designing it so that I did not have print supports or multiple parts glued together. I'm that lazy.
  • The current width (145mm) of the tool holder was a limit imposed by the Lulzbot Mini printing platform size. I started out at 150mm but Cura refused to print that even though the platform is supposedly 155mm wide. If you use a larger printer, you could obviously make the tool holder wider.

The flysky i6 transmitter is great, but it uses ancient AA batteries. I am not going to buy new batteries every few days, therefore I created this battery mod. (Or more accurately I remixed it from the battery cover by benbojangles).

I've added different sizes of the battery cover versions for everyones battery needs, but keep in mind that the flysky transmitter only takes 4 V - 6.5 V. So If you want to use Lithium batteries you'll need a voltage regulator.

If you want to make the same battery mod with the voltmeter from the pictures, you will need the printed part "flysky_battery_mod_10mm_with_voltmeter.stl" and a few additional things. (only this part is optimized for the samsung batteries)

A small voltmeter:
https://www.banggood.com/0_28-Inch-2_5V-30V-Mini-Digital-Voltmeter-p-974258.html?p=C8021898693762017049

https://www.banggood.com/Mini-1A-Lithium-Battery-Charging-Board-Charger-Module-USB-Interface-p-89732.html?p=C8021898693762017049

Connect the Lithium battery with the step up module and the charger. Put the switch between the voltmeter so you can turn it off, and connect the step up module output, which you set to 6 V - 6,5 V, with the AA battery connections on your flysky transmitter.

title: HAM-STD HS1-606 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (41.73g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
I managed to design the micro drone propeller using the HAM-STD HS1-606 airfoil. All tests were done with the Drone Propeller Thrust Tester (all results below).

The part was printed with slow speed, by using a 0.2 extruder nozzle at 0.04 height per layer. I cleaned the print with a Precision Knife

After this, I went on and sanded it using a 500 grit sandpaper.

These are the readings for a few voltage values (you can also view these in the images taken during the test):

  • 1.5V => 12.67 grams
  • 2V => 19.23 grams
  • 2.5V => 30.93 grams
  • 3V => 41.73 grams

The files you can download contain all the pictures taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. Should you want to use this propeller, you should get a bunch of 8520 coreless motors.

Use the SLDPRT files, should you want to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

P.S. Airfoil plotted with the matplotlib library in python.

description.header: Design - How Did We Get Here?
description.text:
This was an iterative design process. It's taught me a great deal about design for FDM printing.

I started out by selecting the tools and taking the necessary measurements. Then I worked to find an orientation of the tools that worked for accessibility. In part the tools decided where they needed to be placed. For example, the screwdrivers needed to be on the top deck, setting the height of that level due to the depth required for the shafts. TinkerCAD seemed the quickest way to get this seemingly simple job done.

The first two designs looked a lot like injection molded products. They were incredibly inefficient for print time and filament use. I had to challenge my conception of what this caddy needed to look like. I definitely did that with the third version. I disposed of the outer shell and connected the remaining structures with 2mm vertical walls. The result was quite hideous. The fourth design disposed of all but the tool "holes" (if you're familiar with TinkerCAD you'll understand.) I started by putting a 2mm thick deck at the required heights. Initially I intended to print the caddy as two parts laying on their backs. That quickly proved problematic leading to the current multi-part concept. The fifth version unified several components and eliminated some over-complication. But I still hadn't included tolerance on the connecting tabs. Mistakenly believing filing and trimming would be sufficient. I was wrong. Version 5.1 should resolve those issues but does not make any major changes to the design since it seems to have some popularity.

There is actually a sixth version of the design which may be posted soon. It addresses some of the odder quirks in the design and uses a very different means of supporting the top deck. I have removed version 4 as I have no intention of solving it's multitude of problems.

Enhance your electronic lab activities with this new PCB Workstation.

And NOW, if you don't own a 3D printer or you quickly want to get this tool, you can order a "ready-to-use" kit!

A complete kit includes the following parts:

  • 1 Modular Base (18x18cm)
  • 4 PCB Holders
  • 8 Crane Arms for Needle Probes
  • 8 Long Needles 40x0,80mm (presoldered to cables)

  • 4 Wing Nuts M5

All the printed parts of the kit are made with a professional-grade 3D printer using high quality materials.

If you want to buy a kit, you can order it paying the total cost (PCB Workstation + shipping) to my PayPal ID [email protected]

https://www.paypal.com/webapps/mpp/send-money-online

Then send me an email ([email protected]) with the following data:

  • First Name Last Name / Company's Name
  • Address
  • ZIP code
  • City
  • Country

Email me at [email protected] if you need any customization of the kit adding parts from the other following products:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:801279
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2111631

Main features:

  • The expensive spring probes used with my previous "PCB Workstation with Crane Arms" have been replaced by cheaper sewing needles, which ensure very precise connections to the electronic board under examination.
  • Each crane arm is equipped with an elastic pressure mechanism that simulates the effect of a spring and thus ensures a stable connection between the needle and the contact point on the electronic board.
  • The base frame allows simultaneous use of numerous articulated arms of both crane type and ball&socket type, making it possible to use the large number of accessories made available with the first edition of my tool (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:801279).
  • The crane arms are now thinner and therefore less bulky, compared to the type provided with the "PCB Workstation with Crane Arms", leaving more space available to the user in the work area where an electronic board is analyzed.

Also have a look at my previous project "PCB Workstation with Crane Arms" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2111631).

Step 1: Mount some bumpers to the base frame

I suggest to apply 5 rubber bumpers under the base frame, so it will be more stable on the desk. You can use bumpers with a diameter up to 20mm.

Step 2: Assemble the PCB holders

The central part of the base consists of 4 sliding pieces arranged in a cross along which can be moved the anchoring blocks to firmly keep the printed circuit board in place. The assembly of the PCB holders to the base piece requires M5 wing nuts (5mm) and M5 hex bolts (5×12 mm). The PCB holders have two faces, one for straight sides, the other for the corners of a printed circuit board. You can choose the right face simply turning the holder.

Step 3: Assemble the articulated arms

Fit the vertical crane arm into the hole of the rotating base support, then mount the horizontal needle arm using a M4 wing nut (4mm) and a M4 hex bolt (4×10 mm).

Step 4: Insert needles soldered to an electric cable

I suggest to use needles of size 40x0.80mm (http://www.amazon.it/gp/product/B0071WCCW4). You can also try 38x0.70mm needles.
Insert a needle-pusher into the hexagonal frame of each needle arm.

Step 5: Add optional parts and accessories

Now that you have almost finished your customized "PCB Workstation", perhaps you would like to add a magnifying glass, or a LED lamp, or even other accessories available from my original project "PCB Workstation with Articulated Arms" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:801279).

remixed_from.author: MKSA
remixed_from.title: Swivel filament guide, the best got better !

description.text:
This swivel guide is far simpler and more effective due to its low mass and elasticity than the ones using bearings or a single ball. The PTFE tube helps reduce friction.

For smooth operation, I concluded it was best to locate the spool holder on the side in such a way the spool is in the same plane as the X/Z. The filament unwinds naturally, no kink, no binding Furthermore the spool that is quite heavy won't interfere with the printer as it is not mounted to it.

As said in the previous version I realized it would be better to give the max flex in the Z axis to smooth the sudden traction/retraction due to the extruder and carriage displacement.

It can be made with just the Flex filament or two filaments, for fun and to get a very firm grip on the 8mm rod.

As can be seen, I managed to use flex filament for the base and PLA for the top by "soldering" a 12cm piece of Flex to the PLA ! See picture. One can also pause the print when the flex is almost gone and introduce the PLA. I used PLA because its working T° is closer to the Flex.

Not much Flex left to experiment with PETG too.

With PLA, you will have to enlarge the opening to avoid cracking it when installing.

IMPORTANT NOTE: After a couple of weeks, the PLA and Flex parts separated. No flex left to experiment with higher T° or with PETG. No problem with full flex and works fine.

Smoothen and round with abrasive the flexible portion to reduce stress concentration that could lead to premature failure.

You can also reduce the flexible part by grinding the sides to make it more flexible if required.

Flare both side of the 4mm PTFE tube after installation.

title: HAM-STD HS1-620 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (31.01g thrust @3V)

description.text:
Note: At 1.5V it barely generated any thrust. Left it for a while thinking something's wrong, but it just hanged at around 0.72-0.75 grams... Weird.
The propeller was designed by using the HAM-STD HS1-620 airfoil. All testing was done on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Tester (test results provided below).

The part was printed with slow speed, with a 0.2 extruder nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The print was cleaned using a Precision Knife

After this, I got to finishing the part with a 400 grit sandpaper.

Here are the measurements for a few voltage presets (you can also check these out in the images):

  • 1.5V => 0.72 grams
  • 2V => 8.11 grams
  • 2.5V => 21.55 grams
  • 3V => 31.01 grams

The included files contain all the pictures taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and the SLDPRT files. If you'd like to use the propeller, make sure you get a 8520 coreless motor.

You should use the SLDPRT files, should you want to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Notice: Airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library in python.

Gloomhaven is a game of Euro-inspired tactical combat in a persistent world of shifting motives. Players will take on the role of a wandering adventurer with their own special set of skills and their own reasons for travelling to this dark corner of the world. Players must work together out of necessity to clear out menacing dungeons and forgotten ruins. In the process they will enhance their abilities with experience and loot, discover new locations to explore and plunder, and expand an ever-branching story fueled by the decisions they make.

Read more about Gloomhaven at Boardgamegeek:

description.text:
Kwanchai's Neolithic Ops is a redesign of Nexus Ops featuring a prehistoric theme.

Kwanchai made a print-and-play version, but when I first saw dutchmogul Shamanic Mammoth Rider I said to myself : I is a perfect mini for Neolithic Ops !
So I started to gather and mix matching minis for Neolithic Ops and I ended by making all the game pieces : Minis, Hex and Tokens.

You still need the original paper Neolithic Ops for the rules, player aids, cards and hex decorations.

More info about Neolithic Ops : https://boardgamegeek.com/filepage/64142/kwanchais-neolithic-ops-redesign-nexus-ops

More info about Nexus Ops : https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/15363/nexus-ops

The quantity to print are in the file names :p
For the Minis, the quantity given is for each player.
For Hexes and Tokens, the quantity given is for the whole game.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Resolution:

0.4mm

Notes:

I printed all the mini and token with 0.4mm extruder.
Monkey, Man, Tiger and Gigantodon, Berry and Tokens print well without support.
Woman and Mammoth need support (for the blowpipe and trunk)

Hex printed with 0.8mm extruder.

The minis

The Monkey is a simple scaling of the great chimp from lordkylo.

The Man is based on dutchmogul's Hunter but I have shorten/enlarged the lance so it was much less fragile.

The Woman was made with DesktopHero Beta (assets from dutchmogul). You will find the saved character in the files if you want to reuse is in the software.

The Mammoth is dutchmogul's Mammoth with a new base and the woman arms enlarged for smaller printing.

The Tiger is Mike's the Tiger from rowiac with saberteeth from MakerBot added. I lifted the head up, lowered the tail and added a permanent support to be able to print him without support.

The Gigantodon is dutchmogul's Guardian Dragon with the wings from the dutchmogul Forest Dragon added.

The Hexs

The Hex are from Srmalloy.
I let the surface blank to glue Kwanchai's very nice drawing.
I modified Srmalloy Openscad script to get the U shaped Triple Hex (you can find it in the files)

Whether it's the scale or the original design, the hexes did not clip AT ALL.
Now they are printed... so I'll keep them, but I would try another type of clipping if I where to print it again.

The tokens

The berries are Razz Berry modified with a numbered base to show the currency (1 or 5). I printed them in two size (10mm and 15mm) to have a direct visual estimation of the currency. I think it works pretty well.

To keep the raspberry theme and cope with the "mine" token, I made some flat raspberry token in OpenSCAD (The raspberry path is made with the great OpenSCAD plugin for Inkscape) The quantity given are though to put raspberry token on the home space too (even if Kwanchai's drawing already have the info).

Finally, I made some exploration tokens with OpenSCAD and I glued Kwanchai's drawing on top of it with a great result (IMHO).

title: Axel's DIY coreXY 3D printer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my DIY CoreXY 3D printer that I have designed. It is a wooden frame with 3D printed parts. All the plastic parts are mounted to the wooden frame using small wood screws. This makes the printer relativity easy to assemble and modify. The printer works well and produces high-quality prints.

Video of the 3D printer here: https://youtu.be/KBK9yOW-9XQ

And old video here: https://youtu.be/wOW3CatZgMQ

I have not made any detailed building instructions or videos how to build it, and I will not do that. My wooden frame is built using 28 mm thick pine wood boards which were available relatively cheap where I live. You may need to adapt the design slightly if you plan to build your own. Do not download this and expect that you can build a printer exactly as mine. Instead, I recommend that you use my design as inspiration for building your own printer. Maybe you can use some of the plastic parts. The download includes a SketchUp file with all the plastic and wooden parts. You can use this file to get the dimensions of all the parts. In this file, it is also possible to see how everything fits together.

Some features of my printer:

  • 20x20x30 cm build volume
  • Heated borosilicate glass printbed
  • “3D-touch” sensor for auto mesh bed leveling
  • Genuine E3D V6 hotend (0.4 mm nozzle)
  • Trinamic TMC2100 stepper drivers
  • MKS GEN 1.4 control board
  • Marlin version 1.1.4 firmware (configuration files included in the download)

My website: http://axelsdiy.brinkeby.se/

Update 2017-08-30
Updated the "XY-jointers" with new versions. A new spool hub is also available. I have also replaced the firmware configuration files with new ones for Marlin version 1.1.4.

Update 2018-02-28
Added new images and added a new video showing more details of the printer. A lot of new high-resolution photos are also available on my website now.

title: HAM-STD HS1-708 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (36.39g thrust @3V)

description.text:
The micro drone propeller has been designed using the HAM-STD HS1-708 airfoil coordinates. Testing was done using the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (all results below).

Part printed at slow speed, with the help of a 0.2mm extruder nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. The print was cleaned with the help of an X-ACTO Knife

After this, I then got to finish the propeller with a 500 grit sandpaper.

Here are the thrust readings for some voltage presets (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 9.42 grams
  • 2V => 14.35 grams
  • 2.5V => 26.28 grams
  • 3V => 36.39 grams

The files that are included contain all pictures relevant to the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the printable STL files and the SLDPRT files. If you want to use this propeller, you should grab a bunch of 8520 coreless motors.

Use the SLDPRT files, should you desire to make your own changes to the propeller.

P.S. The airfoil plotted with the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
A small test bed for a fidget spinner. Ideal to show a bit of physics with it.

Simply connect a LED and LDR and start experimenting.

Connecting it to an oscilloscope you can do a good range of experiments:

  • Calculate RPM (a bit of maths needed depending on the number of arms the fidget spinner has.
  • Observe friction and deceleration. Measure and see how after each turn, the width between pulses shrinks.
  • Calculate angular velocity.
  • Learn to use the horizontal axis of an oscilloscope to compute by hand frequency and measure periods.
  • See the effects of lubrication has on the fidget spinner.

Connect it to an arduino and compute everything with it.

You can also hook up an inductive sensor to do the same measurements! It is your call.

Great for teaching kids a little bit of physics while they use their favourite new gadget.

Vdd --- LDR --- 1K --- GND

This is my new fidget spinner

This is my design for a rotary-dispersed water sprinkler, designed for medium water pressure. My biggest problem is that my garden is pretty large; to the point that an ordinary sprayer won't get all of it. Other sprayer designs end up with no-water zones, so I have to manually move it to get total coverage. This was designed with the idea that I could put it in the middle of the garden, turn it on, and get water to every plant in the garden without moving it. I did mine in PLA, and used a servo retention screw like this:
https://www.servocity.com/media/catalog/product/cache/1/image/438x280/602f0fa2c1f0d1ba5e241f914e856ff9/l/a/large_servo_mounting_screws.jpg

You'll notice the spinner is flat on the bottom of each blade. That's so that you don't have to run with any support; the blades don't start somewhere out in the air. It's a 45-degree angle, so most printers should be able to print it fine.

You will probably have to drill out the center hole in the spinning part; I used a .093" drill. Obviously you could also just heat up a screw and push it through. Screw into the hole on the "base" to retain the spinner. I had significant problems with the "end" part leaking through. My eventual solution was to put some thin CA (superglue) in the bottom and let it dry. You could also use polyurethane I suppose. Just something to seal up those pores in the material. This is something like the 5th version I created; initial versions didn't have the retaining "edge" for a gasket inside where the hose goes. It works much better if you use a gasket, but it's not 100% required. I will probably make a 6th version with oblong discharge holes; in practice it still produces several fine streams that make it completely through the spinner, and end up spreading the water unevenly. I could probably also remedy this by making the spinner have no direct path through the blades; ie there is always a blade in the way of the stream. The other issue is that if you have less-than-clean water, the holes are pretty small, and might plug up. In any case, it works decently well, and has greatly reduced the amount of time I spend moving the sprinkler around. It's not yet perfect, but if you want an interesting sprinkler, give it a try. Oh by the way, the spinner doesn't have enough inertia to hurt your finger, even at full power. If a dog or cat or kid gets close enough to touch it they're going to be soaked anyway!

title: Bosch GluePen holder for OBI pegboards

description.text:
The BOSCH GluePen is very nice!
This holder makes it palpable every time.
And it has a contaner for about 15 glue sticks (7mm)

About my pegboard:
I have buyed a pegboard from OBI (
https://www.obi.de/lochwandsysteme/lochwand-mit-vierkantlochung-1200-mm-breit/p/9178419).

This pegboard has square perforations with 1cm^2. This squares has the advantage for us owner of 3d printers that you can build your own set of items directly out of the printer.
The normal pegboards are only drilled with 3mm holes, so you need metal hooks because the prints will break with that thickness.

I am offering a series of all my prints for this pegboard for using or inspiration of your own items.

Please think about the needed density of your prints when you are slicing!
i have used PLA with a density between 25 and 50% (often with support, some items you have to clue befor using them). A resolution of 0.2 mm should be enough for your pegboard-items.

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/a8gyrC2fUqe

As already stated this is a model of a LT-2 Landing Strut from the game Kerbal Space Program. All the relevant detail that was in the ingame model should be in this model. The dimensions used were just rough just to get the proportion right so the model is roughly 35mm x 200mm x 140mm. The idea is for this to be an ongoing thing so that I would eventually have a mass of parts from the game for everyone to build and print any ship configuration desired by just drag and dropping the parts in an assembly. So keep checking my page for any future parts. If interested, join my group @ http://www.thingiverse.com/groups/design-to-print/topics where I aim to help anybody with anything I can with modeling like this design.

Scale the model to whatever size you wish before printing due to the model being oversized for ease of modeling.
If the model is not in the correct orientation just set to print whatever way you want.
